{{italic title}}

A '''''parti pris'''''<ref>{{cite book|author=James Stevens Curl|title="parti." |work=A Dictionary of Architecture and Landscape Architecture|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=2000|accessdate=May 17, 2009|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1O1-parti.html}}</ref> is an organizing thought or decision behind an architect's [[design]],  presented in the form of a basic diagram or a simple statement.<ref>Ching, Francis D. K. (1995). A Visual Dictionary of Architecture. Van Nostrand Reinhold Company. p. 53. {{ISBN|0-442-02462-2}}.</ref>

It may be shortened to "parti". The term comes from 15th century French, in which "parti pris" meant "decision taken." Later, it took on the meaning of "bias" or "prejudice".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arch100and110.blogspot.com/2012/11/parti.html|title=An Introduction to Architecture and Visual Communications: parti|first=Blue|last=One|date=21 November 2012|website=Arch100and110.blogspot.com|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref>  The term developed in a particularly Euro-centric context of the École des Beaux-Arts in Paris, France in which the proponents were predominantly white, male and well-to-do.

The development of the parti frequently precedes the development of [[Architectural plan|plan]], [[Architectural drawing#Cross section|section]], and [[Architectural drawing#Elevation|elevation]] diagrams.<ref name=medium>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/applying-architecture-to-product-design/applying-architecture-to-product-design-parti-68b0b7345db9#.p0d87v6lc |title=Applying Architecture to Product Design: Parti |last1=Mandelbaum |first1=Melissa |website=Medium.com  |access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref>

Due to the fact that it defines the organizing thought prior to research, exploration, collaboration and the development of intentions, the "parti" is a passé approach to architectural design. Critics argue that recent historical attempts to recover the term for contemporary times are conservative and nostalgic for a simpler time. They make the case that parti is a stand in for a formalist approach to architecture that abdicates responsibility and social engagement.

